<br>
    I don't know if I can follow up such a great post by Uriel, but I'll try.  &quot; Speech impediment...glasses...braces, and damn if my parents didn't dress me funny!!&quot;, this quote reminds me a lot of myself, in fact this was me back around my junior high days.  I still wear glasses (I'll still will not get contact lenses) and I still have a speech impediment, plus the fact that I live like a hermit.  Who knows, maybe that is why I rarely go out and make social appearances.  However, with this in mind and the fact that I always loved played games, dating back to the commader &lt;sp&gt; 64 and atari 2600 days.  Getting into the on-line games was a smooth move due to the reasons mentioned above.  I will always have the game age of empires some where in me.  It was that game that introduced me to the on-line community.  Me, being a loner of sorts, this was a great way to solve them anxiety driven social situations.  It was AoE that made me discover clans/guilds.  These clans/guilds was not only a way to have other people to play with, but a way of communicating to others.  I still stay in contact with them, even though we don't play AoE like we used to, but just the fact you have others recognizing you and talking to you, makes you feel good. You don't know how much that makes you feel happy, gives you confidence in yourself, self-esteem is at a high, and you simply don't feel like a outcast.  To me, its not the game itself that keeps me sane and happy, its the people I'm around with that keeps me playing these games.  There was a time when I really didn't know what a &quot;friend&quot; really meant or what constitudes something to be a friend.  The last past 3-4 years, its finally coming to me what a friend is all about.  I don't care if its on-line or real life.  One needs that kind of mentality to get through life.  True, one must keep self-control over this games--as we all know these types of multi-player games can be very addictive and can lead to very awful consequences.  But, if you do have control over your life and feel satisfied with it, then by all means continue to play these types of games.  As for me, I certainly will, maybe not to the extent that once did.  I do have a sense of dissatisfication, having the need of more of a social life now.  Plus I want to really excel in academics.  Its those two reasons, why I won't be on as much as I used to.  The point being,  these types of multi-player games is more then just a &quot;game&quot; its a way to keep you going in life, might not be the healthiest of sorts, but it sure is a way to stay out of trouble and going insane.  To tell you the truth, Everquest and AoE is a main reason I got through the last few years (not in all positive aspects, but still contributed in many ways).  Now, I do have some kind of social life and I'm damn happy about it.  However, these games will always have a home in my heart.  More so the people I've met and become friends with.  I'm not trying to get any sympathy votes or any responses, in fact, this is the first time I'm ever posting a message like this on-line.  I just wanted to say thank you.  May god bless and take care of you all.<br>
